  "prompt": "What's the most embarrassing thing you've ever said in another language by accident?",
  "response": "Ah, language mishaps can be both cringe-worthy and hilarious in hindsight! One classic example is confusing words that sound similar but have *very* different meanings. For instance:\n\n- In Spanish, saying **\"Estoy embarazada\"** (I\u2019m pregnant) instead of **\"Estoy avergonzado/a\"** (I\u2019m embarrassed). The word *embarazada* looks like *embarrassed*, but it means *pregnant*\u2014leading to some very confused looks!\n\n- In French, mixing up **\"Je suis excit\u00e9(e)**\" (I\u2019m excited) with **\"Je suis enthousiaste\"**. While *excit\u00e9* technically means *excited*, it\u2019s often interpreted in a more... *adult* way, so it\u2019s better to stick with *enthousiaste* for everyday excitement.\n\n- In German, confusing **\"Ich bin warm\"** (I am warm) with **\"Mir ist warm\"** (I feel warm). Saying *Ich bin warm* implies you\u2019re a warm object, not that you\u2019re feeling warm\u2014cue some strange glances!\n\nThese slip-ups are all part of the language-learning journey. What about you? Do you have any linguistic blunders to share? \ud83d\ude04",
  "temperature": 1.0,
